The four Catalyst plans.

When you call an action, your dataframe chain travels through Catalyst as four distinct plans before hitting the cluster.

First, the parsed logical plan. This is your code as a tree of unresolved references. Column names are still strings; types are unknown.

Second, the analyzed logical plan. Catalyst resolves column names against the schema, checks types, and binds function calls. Errors at this stage look like analysis exceptions.

Third, the optimized logical plan. This is where the rule-based rewrites happen — predicate pushdown moves filters toward the scan, projection pruning drops unused columns, constant folding evaluates simple arithmetic at plan time, and so on.

Fourth, the physical plan. Catalyst picks operators — hash aggregate versus sort aggregate, broadcast hash join versus sort merge join — and a physical strategy. The output of this stage is what actually runs on executors.

You can inspect each plan by calling explain with extended equals true.
